---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Newsletter from '../components/Newsletter.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Legal — Legal Sovereignty"
  description="The Legal pillar at AfterChildren. The five essential documents, Medicaid asset protection, inheritance, digital estate, end-of-life planning. The walls that protect everything you have built — built deliberately, while you are still well."
>
  <!-- PILLAR HERO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="pillar-hero">
      <p class="pillar-hero__eyebrow">Sovereignty 04</p>
      <h1 class="pillar-hero__title">
        Legal.<br />
        <em>The walls everything else lives behind.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="pillar-hero__lede">
        About 60% of American adults do not have a will. Of those who do, more than half wrote it ten or more years ago, when the laws were different, the children were younger, the assets were smaller, and the people named in the documents were sometimes not yet divorced, deceased, or estranged. The estate plan you do not have, or the one you wrote in 2009, is the single largest unforced error available to anyone reading this site. The fix is mostly mechanical, mostly inexpensive, and mostly takes one Saturday. The cost of not doing it is what gets distributed to your family at the worst possible moment of their lives.
      </p>
      <div class="pillar-hero__meta">
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">22</span> planned articles in this pillar</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">0</span> live now</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span>First article ships next week</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHERE TO START -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="start-panel">
      <p class="start-panel__eyebrow">Where to start</p>
      <h2 class="start-panel__title">Three documents. This Saturday. Not next year.</h2>
      <ol class="start-panel__list">
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Write or update your will</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">If you do not have one, you are in the 60% who has decided to let your state distribute your assets by default formula. If you have one written before 2018, the federal estate tax thresholds, beneficiary rules, and digital asset laws have all changed underneath you. A current online will from a reputable service costs $99 to $299 and takes 45 minutes. The lawyer version costs $400 to $1,500. Both are dramatically better than nothing.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Sign a Durable Power of Attorney</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">If you become incapacitated tomorrow, somebody has to pay your mortgage, file your taxes, and manage your accounts. Without a Durable POA naming that person, your family has to petition a court for conservatorship — a process that takes months, costs thousands, and is publicly recorded. The document costs about $50 online. It is the single highest-leverage legal instrument available to you.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Sign a Healthcare Directive + HIPAA release</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">If you are unconscious in an emergency room, somebody has to decide whether you want the ventilator, the feeding tube, the resuscitation. Without an advance directive, that decision falls to your spouse or children at the worst possible moment, without your guidance, often in disagreement with each other. The HIPAA release lets them talk to your doctors at all. Both documents are free in most states. Both are stored where they can be found.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURED MANIFESTO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="featured">
      <p class="featured__eyebrow">Start here</p>
      <a href="/manifestos/adult-children-not-retirement-plan" class="featured__card">
        <div class="featured__meta">
          <span class="featured__tag">Manifesto</span>
          <span class="featured__time">15 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="featured__title">The Hardest Truth: Your Adult Children Are Not Your Retirement Plan</h2>
        <p class="featured__excerpt">The legal structure most middle-class parents have never heard of, and why it has to be built by your early 60s, not your late 70s. Includes the Medicaid five-year lookback rule, irrevocable trust strategy, and elder-law attorney ROI math — the part of estate planning most lawyers will not bring up unless you ask.</p>
        <span class="featured__cta">Read the essay <span class="featured__arrow">→</span></span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE SIX LEGAL SUB-PILLARS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="subpillars">
      <p class="subpillars__eyebrow">The six legal domains</p>
      <h2 class="subpillars__title">The legal sovereignty work, broken down.</h2>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">01</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">The five essential documents</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Every adult over 55 needs five documents in place: a current will, a durable power of attorney, a healthcare directive (sometimes called a living will), a HIPAA authorization, and — for most families with meaningful assets — a revocable living trust. Together these five cover roughly 95% of the legal situations that arise in the second half of life. Most people have one of them. Most people who have all five had to be told what HIPAA was. This sub-pillar is the cornerstone of the entire Legal section. If you read nothing else here, read this.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Five Documents Every Adult Over 55 Needs (And Most People Don't Have)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Will vs. Trust: Which One Do You Actually Need?</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Durable Power of Attorney: The Document That Prevents Conservatorship</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Healthcare Directives and Living Wills: What to Specify, Word by Word</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> HIPAA Authorization: The Free Document Almost Nobody Knows About</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">02</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Estate planning strategy</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The documents are mechanical. The strategy is not. Choosing between a will and a trust depends on your state, your assets, your family structure, and your privacy preferences. Probate avoidance matters in California, Texas, and Florida far more than in Pennsylvania or Wisconsin. Beneficiary designations on retirement accounts override your will, which means a 401(k) that still lists your ex-spouse from 2007 will pay out to your ex-spouse regardless of what your current will says. Most estate plans fail not in the documents but in the strategy underneath them.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Estate Planning Without a Lawyer: What You Can DIY (And What You Can't)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Probate Avoidance: When It Matters and When It Doesn't</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Beneficiary Designations: The Override That Beats Your Will</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Joint Accounts and Tenancy: The Estate Planning Tool Most Couples Use Wrong</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Estate Tax Threshold in 2026: Why It Probably Doesn't Apply to You</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">03</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Medicaid asset protection</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The single highest-stakes legal decision available to middle-class parents — and the one that has to be made earliest. Medicaid will pay for nursing home care only after you have spent down nearly all your assets. There are legal strategies to restructure assets in advance so that you qualify without losing the house and the savings to the state. The catch is the five-year lookback rule: most transfers have to happen at least five years before you apply. This means the planning conversation has to happen in your early 60s, not your late 70s. A good elder-law attorney charges $4,000 to $10,000 for a comprehensive plan. For most parents with $300K to $1.5M in net worth, it is the single highest-ROI legal expense available.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Medicaid Planning: The Five-Year Lookback Rule Explained</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Medicaid Asset Protection Trusts: How They Work, When They Make Sense</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The House and Medicaid: What's Protected, What Isn't</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Finding an Elder-Law Attorney: The Three Questions to Ask First</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">04</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Inheritance &amp; beneficiaries</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The inheritance conversation is the one almost nobody has, until it is forced. By the time it is forced, the parents are not in a position to lead it, and the adult children are guessing at the wishes nobody documented. Equal distribution is not always the right answer. Blended families, special-needs children, financially struggling children, estranged children, and adult children with high-conflict marriages all introduce structural questions that require deliberate decisions, not default formulas. The conversation, had at 65 with all parties present, is dramatically better than the alternative.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Inheritance Conversation Nobody Wants to Have (And How to Lead It)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> How to Protect Your Money From an Adult Child's Bad Marriage</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Unequal Inheritance: When It's the Right Call, and How to Explain It</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Special Needs Trusts: The Estate Planning Tool That Protects a Vulnerable Child</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Disinheriting an Adult Child: The Legal Reality, and the Family Reality</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">05</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Digital estate &amp; legacy</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Most people over 55 now have between 40 and 200 online accounts: email, banking, brokerage, social media, cloud storage, subscription services, photo archives, cryptocurrency, frequent-flyer miles. When you die, almost none of this is accessible to your family by default. Twenty years of family photos, locked behind a password nobody knows. Bank accounts, lost because the executor cannot prove identity to the platform. This sub-pillar exists because the estate-planning industry has not caught up, and the gap is now a real one. The fix takes one afternoon with a password manager and a properly-drafted digital estate clause in your will.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Digital Estate: 40+ Accounts Your Family Cannot Access After You Die</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Password Managers as Estate Planning Tools: The Setup That Actually Works</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Cryptocurrency and Estate Planning: The Lost-Wallet Problem</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Cloud Photos, Family Archives, and the 50-Year Storage Question</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">06</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">End-of-life planning</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Pre-planning your funeral is the gift to your family that nobody talks about giving. The average funeral costs $9,000 to $12,000. The funeral industry has well-documented sales practices that exploit grief to upsell at the worst possible moment. Pre-planning — sometimes called pre-need arrangement — locks in costs, documents preferences, and removes the worst decision from your family on the worst day. Add organ donation, advance medical directives at the actual end of life, and a clear conversation with your healthcare proxy, and you have done the second-most-important piece of late-stage legal work. The first is the documents above.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Pre-Planning a Funeral: The Gift to Your Family Nobody Talks About</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Cremation, Burial, Green Burial, Aquamation: The 2026 Options Compared</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Organ Donation: How It Actually Works, What to Specify</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The DNR / DNI / POLST Distinction: Words That Decide Everything</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Letter to Your Family: What to Write, and Where to Put It</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMITMENTS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="commitments">
      <p class="commitments__eyebrow">Our legal-content rules</p>
      <h2 class="commitments__title">What we promise on every legal page.</h2>
      <div class="commitments__grid">
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Not legal advice</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on this site are independent journalism, not legal advice. Estate law varies by state, sometimes by county. We tell you the general framework. We tell you which decisions need a local attorney and which can be safely done with an online service. We do not draft your documents and we are not your lawyer. We do, however, give you the questions to ask the lawyer you hire.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Online versus attorney, honestly</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">For about 70% of middle-class families, an online will and document service is genuinely good enough. For the other 30% — blended families, business owners, high net worth, special-needs children, multi-state property, Medicaid planning — the lawyer is non-negotiable. We tell you which side of that line you are on, by name, by situation. We do not push you to the attorney to earn higher affiliate commissions, and we do not push you to the online service when the situation needs more.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">State-aware content</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Estate law is state law. A will valid in Texas may not be valid in New York. Probate rules in California are different from probate rules in Florida. When state variation matters, we say so, name the states where the rule differs, and direct you to the right local resource. We do not publish content that pretends estate law is uniform across the country.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Reviewer layer (rolling out)</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on legal topics will progressively carry a "Reviewed by [Name, Credential]" line as we bring on credentialed reviewers — an estate planning attorney for documents and probate content, an elder-law attorney for Medicaid material, a tax professional for estate-tax pieces. Until then, articles in this section are bylined by M. Holloway, the founder, or the AfterChildren Editorial Desk.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- AFFILIATES -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="affiliates">
      <p class="affiliates__eyebrow">Affiliate disclosure</p>
      <h2 class="affiliates__title">What we link to, and what we earn.</h2>
      <p class="affiliates__intro">When we recommend a service, we link to it. When the link earns us a commission, we disclose it. Legal services have an unusually wide quality range, from excellent to predatory. We will only link to services that meet a clear competence bar — proper licensing, transparent pricing, verified track record, and document quality reviewed against attorney standards.</p>
      <p class="affiliates__intro affiliates__intro--secondary">As this pillar develops, the partner list below will become live affiliate links. Until then, the list documents the categories under evaluation. Each gets a published review before any link goes live.</p>
      <div class="affiliates__list">
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Online will &amp; estate documents</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">For the 70% of families whose situation does not require an attorney. Under evaluation: Trust &amp; Will, Snug, FreeWill, Wealth.com. Each gets a side-by-side comparison before any link goes live.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Elder-law attorney matching</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">For Medicaid asset protection and complex estate planning. Vetted by National Academy of Elder Law Attorneys (NAELA) certification. Under evaluation: NAELA directory (free), ElderLawAnswers, local bar association referral services.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Estate planning attorney matching</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">For trusts, complex wills, blended families, business succession. Under evaluation: Avvo, Martindale-Hubbell ratings, ACTEC member directory for high-net-worth situations.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Password managers</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">The digital estate solution. We will recommend tools that support legacy access (designating someone to receive your passwords on your death). Under evaluation: 1Password, Bitwarden, Dashlane.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Funeral pre-planning</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Transparent, no-pressure pre-need arrangements that lock in pricing and document preferences. We will not link to high-pressure cemetery sales operations. Under evaluation: Tulip Cremation, Funeralocity, Solace.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Digital legacy services</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Services that manage the transfer of digital assets, accounts, and photo archives after death. Under evaluation: Cake End-of-Life Planning, Everplans, Empathy.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA: ASK A QUESTION -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="ask">
      <h2 class="ask__title">A legal question we should answer?</h2>
      <p class="ask__lede">If a Legal topic is on your mind and not on the list above, send it. We read everything. We cannot give legal advice for your specific situation, but the most-asked questions become next month's articles.</p>
      <p class="ask__contact">Write to <a href="mailto:editor@afterchildren.com">editor@afterchildren.com</a> with subject line "Legal: [topic]".</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Newsletter />
</Base>

